05666nam a22009255i 9780812291407DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20152015pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979910552  a97808122914077 a10.9783/97808122914072doi  a(DE-B1597)451285  a(OCoLC)907964739  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aTJ211b.T74 2015 7aHIS0370102bisacsh04a629.82231 aTruitt, E. R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMedieval Robots :bMechanism, Magic, Nature, and Art /cE. R. Truitt. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2015] 4cÂ©2015  a1 online resource (296 p.) :b36 color illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Middle Ages Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction. The Persistence of Robots: An Archaeology of Automata -- tChapter 1. Rare Devices: Geography and Technology -- tChapter 2. Between Art and Nature: Natura artifex, Neoplatonism, and Literary Automata -- tChapter 3. Talking Heads: Astral Science, Divination, and Legends of Medieval Philosophers -- tChapter 4. The Quick and the Dead: Corpses, Memorial Statues, and Automata -- tChapter 5. From Texts to Technology: Mechanical Marvels in Courtly and Public Pageantry -- tChapter 6. The Clockwork Universe: Keeping Sacred and Secular Time -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA thousand years before Isaac Asimov set down his Three Laws of Robotics, real and imagined automata appeared in European courts, liturgies, and literary texts. Medieval robots took such forms as talking statues, mechanical animals, and silent metal guardians; some served to entertain or instruct while others performed disciplinary or surveillance functions. Variously ascribed to artisanal genius, inexplicable cosmic forces, or demonic powers, these marvelous fabrications raised fundamental questions about knowledge, nature, and divine purpose in the Middle Ages.Medieval Robots recovers the forgotten history of fantastical, aspirational, and terrifying machines that captivated Europe in imagination and reality between the ninth and fourteenth centuries. E. R. Truitt traces the different forms of self-moving or self-sustaining manufactured objects from their earliest appearances in the Latin West through centuries of mechanical and literary invention. Chronicled in romances and song as well as histories and encyclopedias, medieval automata were powerful cultural objects that probed the limits of natural philosophy, illuminated and challenged definitions of life and death, and epitomized the transformative and threatening potential of foreign knowledge and culture. This original and wide-ranging study reveals the convergence of science, technology, and imagination in medieval culture and demonstrates the striking similarities between medieval and modern robotic and cybernetic visions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAutomataxHistorydTo 1500. 0aCivilization, Medieval. 0aImaginationxHistoryvTo 1500. 0aImaginationxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aMachine theoryxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aMagicxHistoryvTo 1500. 0aMagicxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aMechanical engineeringxHistoryvTo 1500. 0aMechanical engineeringxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aMechanical toysxHistoryvTo 1500. 0aMechanical toysxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aNature and civilizationxHistoryvTo 1500. 0aNature and civilizationxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aRobotsxHistoryvTo 1500. 0aRobotsxHistoryyTo 1500. 4aMedieval and Renaissance Studies. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aHistory.  aMedieval and Renaissance Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2015z978311043